.TH LUAINSTALLER 1 "June 2026" "luainstaller v1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
luainstaller \- bundle Lua projects into distributable executables (Windows/Linux)

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B luainstaller
.BR bundle " " \fIentry.lua\fR
.RI [ options ]
.br
.B luainstaller
.BR analyze " " \fIentry.lua\fR
.RI [ options ]
.br
.B luainstaller
.BR version

.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBluainstaller\fR is a tool that packages Lua projects into \fBdistributable executables\fR,
supporting \fBWindows\fR and \fBLinux\fR. It is open-sourced on GitHub and licensed under the
\fBLGPL\fR. See the repository for source code, releases, and documentation:
https://github.com/Water-Run/luainstaller

\fBluainstaller\fR provides dependency analysis and single-file bundling capabilities, and can
package non-pure-Lua content inside the wrapper program. It is important to note that
\fBluainstaller\fR guarantees that the packaged binary will run on the same \fBsystem environment\fR
as yours (excluding the \fBlua\fR environment itself).

\fBluainstaller\fR can be used as a CLI tool and (when installed via LuaRocks) as a Lua module via
\fBrequire("luainstaller")\fR.

.SH INSTALLATION
Install via LuaRocks:
.nf
luarocks install luainstaller
.fi
This installs the \fBluainstaller\fR CLI and the Lua module.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B bundle
Bundle an entry script and its dependencies into a distributable program. By default, output is a
directory; use \fB--onefile\fR for a single-file executable.
.TP
.B analyze
Analyze dependencies only; no bundling output is produced.
.TP
.B version
Print the version information.

.SH CLI USAGE
The CLI tool name is \fBluainstaller\fR.

.SS Help
.nf
luainstaller --help
.fi
Typical output:
.nf
luainstaller v1.0.0

Usage:
  luainstaller bundle <entry.lua> [options]
  luainstaller analyze <entry.lua> [options]
  luainstaller version

Options:
  ...
.fi

.SS bundle
\fBbundle\fR is the most commonly used command, used to package a Lua project into an executable.

Default mode (output a directory):
.nf
luainstaller bundle \fIentry.lua\fR
.fi
Typical output:
.nf
success.
\fIentry.lua\fR => \fIoutput_dir\fR/
.fi

By default, \fBluainstaller\fR performs \fBstatic dependency analysis\fR starting from the entry
\fB.lua\fR file and outputs all required runtime files into a directory.

Single-file mode (\fB--onefile\fR, output a single executable):
.nf
luainstaller bundle \fIentry.lua\fR --onefile
.fi
Typical output:
.nf
success.
\fIentry.lua\fR => \fIoutput_file\fR
.fi
\fB--onefile\fR further wraps the directory bundle output into a \fBsingle executable file\fR.

.SS analyze
Analyze dependencies only:
.nf
luainstaller analyze \fIentry.lua\fR
.fi
Typical output:
.nf
success.
N dependencies found:
  1) ...
  2) ...
.fi

.SH OPTIONS
The following options apply to \fBbundle\fR and/or \fBanalyze\fR as described.

.TP
.BI \-o ", " \-\-out " " path
Output path.
For \fBbundle\fR: a directory path in default mode, or a file path when \fB--onefile\fR is set.
Examples:
.nf
luainstaller bundle main.lua --out ../dist/
luainstaller bundle main.lua --onefile --out ../dist/app.exe
.fi

.TP
.B \-\-onefile
Generate a single-file executable. Default output is a directory.

.TP
.BI \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Enable verbose analysis and bundling logs.
.nf
luainstaller bundle main.lua --verbose
.fi

.TP
.BI \-\-max\-deps " " n
Maximum number of dependencies allowed (default: 36).
.nf
luainstaller bundle main.lua --max-deps 100
luainstaller analyze main.lua --max-deps 50
.fi

.TP
.BI \-\-include " " path
Manually include additional dependencies. May be specified multiple times.
Use this for dynamic \fBrequire\fR patterns that static analysis cannot detect.
.nf
luainstaller bundle main.lua --include ./require.lua --include ./plugin.lua
.fi

.TP
.BI \-\-exclude " " path
Manually exclude dependencies. May be specified multiple times.
Use this to remove false positives (for example, \fBpcall(require, ...)\fR patterns); takes priority
over \fB--include\fR.
.nf
luainstaller bundle main.lua --exclude ./test_utils.lua
.fi

.TP
.B \-\-no\-depscan
Disable dependency scanning. This switches to a fully manual mode where you must specify all
dependencies via \fB--include\fR.
.nf
luainstaller bundle main.lua --no-depscan --include ./a.lua --include ./b.lua
.fi

.TP
.B \-\-icon " " path (Windows only)
Set the application icon (\fB.ico\fR file).
.nf
luainstaller bundle main.lua --onefile --icon ./logo.ico
.fi

.SH LUA API
When installed via LuaRocks, \fBluainstaller\fR can be invoked from Lua. The Lua API uses the same
parameter semantics as the CLI. Dependency scanning is enabled by default; set
\fBdepscan = false\fR to disable it.

.nf
local luainstaller = require("luainstaller")
.fi

.SS bundle
Function signature:
.nf
local ok, out = luainstaller.bundle(opts)
.fi
Return values: when \fBok=true\fR, \fBout\fR is the output path; when \fBok=false\fR, \fBout\fR is an
error message string.

Parameters (\fIopts\fR table):

.TS
lB lB lB lB
l l l l.
Parameter	Type	Default	Description
_
\fBentry\fR	string	required	Entry script path
\fBout\fR	string	\-	Output path (directory when \fBonefile=false\fR; file when \fBonefile=true\fR)
\fBonefile\fR	boolean	\fBfalse\fR	Single-file mode switch
\fBverbose\fR	boolean	\fBfalse\fR	Whether to output detailed logs
\fBmax_deps\fR	number	\fB36\fR	Maximum number of dependencies
\fBinclude\fR	string[]	\fB{}\fR	Manually include dependencies
\fBexclude\fR	string[]	\fB{}\fR	Manually exclude dependencies (priority over \fBinclude\fR)
\fBdepscan\fR	boolean	\fBtrue\fR	Enable automatic dependency analysis
\fBicon\fR	string	\-	Application icon path (\fB.ico\fR file, Windows only)
.TE

Example:
.nf
-- Simplest bundling: output directory, automatic dependency scanning
local ok, out = luainstaller.bundle({ entry = "main.lua" })
if ok then print("Bundle succeeded: " .. out)
else      print("Bundle failed: " .. out) end

-- Single-file mode
local ok, out = luainstaller.bundle({
  entry   = "main.lua",
  onefile = true,
  out     = "../dist/app.exe",
})
.fi

.SS analyze
Function signature:
.nf
local ok, deps = luainstaller.analyze(entry, opts)
.fi
Return values: when \fBok=true\fR, \fBdeps\fR is an array of dependency path strings; when
\fBok=false\fR, \fBdeps\fR is an error message string.

Parameters:

.TS
lB lB lB lB
l l l l.
Parameter	Type	Default	Description
_
\fBentry\fR	string	required	Entry script path
\fIopts\fR.\fBmax_deps\fR	number	\fB36\fR	Maximum number of dependencies
\fIopts\fR.\fBdepscan\fR	boolean	\fBtrue\fR	Enable automatic dependency analysis
.TE

Example:
.nf
local ok, deps = luainstaller.analyze("main.lua")
if ok then
  print("Found " .. #deps .. " dependencies")
  for i, dep in ipairs(deps) do
    print(string.format("  %d) %s", i, dep))
  end
else
  print("Analysis failed: " .. deps)
end
.fi
.RB "Note: " analyze " only performs dependency analysis and produces no bundling artifacts. It
is suitable for pre-checking whether all dependencies are complete and whether any false
positives exist before performing the actual bundle."

.SS version
.nf
print("luainstaller version: " .. luainstaller.version())
.fi

.SH HOW IT WORKS
The workflow of \fBluainstaller\fR can be summarized as: \fBanalyze entry script\fR \-> \fBcollect
dependencies\fR \-> \fBbuild executable\fR \-> \fBoptionally wrap into a single file\fR.

When \fBbundle\fR is executed, \fBluainstaller\fR first performs \fBstatic dependency analysis\fR
starting from the entry \fB.lua\fR file. It scans the source code for common reference patterns
such as \fBrequire(...)\fR, recursively finding all Lua files the project depends on. For cases
that static analysis cannot fully cover \(em such as runtime module name concatenation or
conditional module loading \(em dependencies can be supplemented manually via \fB--include\fR and
false positives can be removed via \fB--exclude\fR.

Once the dependency set is determined, \fBluainstaller\fR organizes the entry script and the
collected Lua code into a bundle set ready for packaging. For pure Lua projects, this step
typically only involves the scripts themselves; for projects containing non-pure-Lua content,
additional files must also be handled to ensure the final artifact runs correctly on the
\fBsame system environment\fR.

In the executable generation stage, \fBluainstaller\fR uses \fBluastatic\fR as its core backend,
paired with a \fBGCC-compatible toolchain\fR to complete compilation and linking. The fundamental
approach is not to rely on a pre-installed \fBlua\fR environment on the target machine to run
scripts, but instead to construct the Lua program and related content into a directly
distributable program. On Windows, if \fB--icon\fR is specified, \fBwindres\fR is additionally
used to compile icon resources into the final executable.

By default, \fBluainstaller\fR uses \fBdirectory output mode\fR: it generates an output directory
containing the executable and required files. When \fB--onefile\fR is enabled, it further
performs \fBsingle-file packaging\fR on top of this, bundling all runtime content into a single
standalone executable for easier distribution and deployment.

Overall, \fBluainstaller\fR's technology stack remains fairly straightforward: the Lua side
handles the CLI, dependency analysis, and bundling process control; \fBluastatic\fR handles the
static integration of the Lua program; the GCC-compatible toolchain handles final compilation
and linking; and \fBwindres\fR handles icon and other resource embedding on Windows.

